==A==
{{glossary}}

{{term|term= Advance-deposit wagering}}
{{defn|defn= [[Advance-deposit wagering]] (ADW) is a form of horse race gambling in which the bettor must fund his or her account before being allowed to place bets. ADW is often conducted online or by phone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Report of Impact of Account Wagering Providers| url=http://www.gaming.ny.gov/pdf/09191215442609.14.12.adwreport.pdf|accessdate=31 August 2014}}</ref>}}

{{term|term= Allowance race}}
{{defn|defn= A race for which entries are restricted to horses meeting certain earnings or other race criteria.<ref name=Lyons6>Price, et al. ''Lyons Press Horseman's Dictionary'' p. 6</ref> The track operator's designated official (usually the Racing Secretary) establishes specific conditions that determine what weights are to be carried by any competing horse based on factors from the horse's previous performances including races won and/or earnings.<ref name="equibase defs"/>  }}

{{term|term= Allowances}}
{{defn|defn= Adjustments in weight "allowed" in a race. Examples are those granted because an apprentice is riding, for three-year-olds running against older horses, or for female horses running against male horses.  Sometimes the conditions of a particular race allow weight allowances for other reasons.<ref name="equibase defs" />}}

{{term|term= Allowance optional claiming}} 
{{defn|defn= ''See'' Optional claiming}}

{{term|term= Also eligible}}
{{defn|defn=A horse officially entered in a race who is not allowed to start because the field is too large, an also-eligible horse is allowed to enter if other horses are scratched prior to a set deadline.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{term|term= Apprentice}}
{{defn|defn= A young [[jockey]], sometimes called a  "bug," who is still in training. An apprentice is required to ride a given number of winners in a specified period of time before completing his or her apprenticeship.<ref name="Hersh25Sept">{{cite web|last1=Hersh|first1=Marcus|title=Growing pains: The journey of an apprentice jockey|url=http://www.drf.com/news/growing-pains-journey-apprentice-jockey|website=Daily Racing Form|accessdate=20 May 2016|date=September 25, 2013}}</ref>   }}

{{glossary end}}

==B==
{{glossary}}
{{term|term= Backside}}
{{defn|defn=Also sometimes called the backstretch (see "backstretch", ''below''), an area with restricted access, usually behind the track, where the [[stable]]s and residential living areas for staff are located.<ref name=Kiesler>{{cite journal|last1=Kiesler|first1=Joseph|last2=Vaughn|first2=Lisa M.|last3=Kaur|first3=Gupreet|title="Voicing" the Social Determinants of Health on the Backside of a Horse Racetrack|journal=Journal of Health Care for the Poor and Underserved|date=2013|volume=24|issue=3|pages=1074–1088|doi=10.1353/hpu.2013.0153}}</ref>}}

{{term|term= [[Backstretch]]}}
{{defn|defn= The straightway on the farther side of an elliptical or oval racecourse. It typically runs parallel to the grandstand and the homestretch where the finish line is located.<ref name="Price 14">{{cite book|last=Price|title=Backstretch|year=2003|page=14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xEZL0A5FZLwC&lpg=PA14&dq=backstretch%20terms%20horse&pg=PA14#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> Also refers to the stabling area adjacent to the racetrack (see "backside", ''above'').<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{term|Bearing In (or out)}}
{{defn|defn= When a horse does not run straight on the course. There are many causes, including fatigue, infirmity, reaction to being whipped, or the rider's inability to control the horse.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{term|term=Black type}}
{{defn|defn=In a sales catalogue, black type is boldface print and indicates a stakes winner if the name is in all caps, or a stakes-placed runner if in upper and lower mixed case letters.<ref name="WA Thoroughbred"/>}}

{{term|term=Blanket finish}}
{{defn|defn= A finish "so close that a blanket would cover all the contestants involved."<ref name="Dict.com">{{cite web|last=Staff|publisher=Dictionary.com|title=Blanket finish|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/blanket+finish|accessdate=12 June 2013}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Bled}}
{{defn|defn=When a horse bleeds from the nostrils either during the running of a race, or when returning to be unsaddled. May explain a poor effort<ref name="equibase defs" /> See also [[Furosemide]] (Lasix).}}

{{term|term=Blinkers}}
{{defn|defn=A hood designed with partial cups behind the horse's eyes that limit a horse's rear vision and some side vision, depending on design.  Blinkers may prevent a horse from ducking away from objects or other horses.<ref name="equibase defs" />}}

{{term|term=Bloodstock agent}}
{{defn|defn= People who specialize in buying and selling horses on behalf of clients and offer advice on purchasing horses.<ref name=nusser>{{cite book|last=Nusser|first=Susan|title=Kentucky Derby Dreams: The Making of Thoroughbred Champions|year=2012|publisher=Macmillan|location=New York|isbn=9780312569907|page=250|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JZhpNxMluRgC&lpg=PA250&dq=%22bloodstock%20agent%22%20glossary&pg=PA250#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>''See also: Pinhooking''}}

{{term|term=Blue hen}}
{{defn|defn= A mare who produces many high quality offspring who also have a significant impact on the breed.<ref name="WA Thoroughbred">{{cite web|last=Staff|title=Thoroughbred Terminology|url=http://www.washingtonthoroughbred.com/magazine/Terms.htm|publisher=Washington Thoroughbred Breeders Association|accessdate=2013-08-27}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Book}}
{{defn|defn=1) The list of mares that a stallion will breed in a given breeding season. A full book is when the maximum number of mares the stallion is deemed able to breed has been reached. 2) A jockey's riding commitments for races. An agent usually is the person who manages and books the races a jockey is to ride.<ref name="equibase defs" />}}

{{term|term=Bounce}}
{{defn|defn=A horse that runs a poor race directly following a career-best or near-best performance.<ref name="equibase defs" />}}

{{term|term=Break or broke}}
{{defn|defn= To leave the starting gate in the initial strides of a race.<ref>{{cite book|last=Price|title=Broke|year=2003|page=24|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xEZL0A5FZLwC&lpg=PA14&dq=backstretch%20terms%20horse&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Break maiden}}
{{defn|defn= When a horse wins a race for the first time in its career.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{term|term=Breather}}
{{defn|defn=Allowing a horse to slow or to run easy for a short distance in a race for the purpose of conserving the horse's stamina or allowing the horse to regain his strength.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{term|term=Breeze}}
{{defn|defn=1. To win easily.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ammer|first=Christine|title=The American Heritage Dictionary of Idioms, Second Edition|year=2013|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|location=New York|isbn=0547676581|page=57|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9QuEiIMaBt0C&lpg=PA57&dq=horse%20racing%20terms%20breeze&pg=PA57#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> 2. A timed workout where the horse is not being asked for full speed; less effort than handily;<ref name="DRF terms" /> or can refer to a light training workout over a short distance that is used to gauge a horse's racing potential and performance.<ref name="Price 26">{{cite book|last=Price|title=Breeze|year=2003|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xEZL0A5FZLwC&lpg=PA26}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Broke down}}
{{defn|defn= A horse that has a serious leg problem during a race where he is limping or cannot put a limb on the ground, resulting in either being removed from the track in a horse ambulance or, in the worst cases, [[animal euthanasia|euthanized]].<ref name="equibase comments">{{cite web|url=http://www.equibase.com/products/cc-comments.cfm |title=Guide to Race Comments|publisher=Equibase.com|accessdate=2014-01-10}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Bullet or bullet work}}
{{defn|defn=The best workout time at a track on a given day at a specific distance.  The past performance listings indicate this work by a printer's "bullet" in front of that particular workout time.<ref name="equibase defs"/>}}

{{term|term=Butazolidin or bute}}
{{defn|defn= See Phenylbutazone, below.}}

{{glossary end}}

==C==
{{glossary}}

{{term|term=Chart}}
{{defn|A detailed list of statistics about a race.  The chart lists the position of each horse at various points of the race, the margin between horses, plus the odds for the race, and each horse's sex, age, weight carried, owner, and trainer.  The chart also describes the purse, race conditions, the prices paid for various winning bets, winning times and so on.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{term|term=Chute}}
{{defn|defn= An extension to a straightaway on either the homestretch or the backstretch used for establishing a distance to eliminate the need to begin the race on a turn.<ref name="equibase defs"/>}}

{{term|term=Circle the field}}
{{defn|defn= When a horse is forced to go very wide around other horses in order to move into a winning position.<ref>{{cite web|title=Quotes from the $100,000 Sycamore (G3) {{!}} Keeneland Thoroughbred Racing and Sales|url=https://www.keeneland.com/racing/quotes-100000-sycamore-g3-3|website=www.keeneland.com|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Haskin|first1=Steve|title=The Greatest Performance No One Has Seen|url=http://cs.bloodhorse.com/blogs/horse-racing-steve-haskin/archive/2017/05/24/the-greatest-performance-no-one-ever-saw.aspx|website=Blood Horse|accessdate=10 August 2017|language=en|date=24 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gurnick|first1=Ken|title=HORSE RACING; General Challenge Circles Field to Win at Santa Anita|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/05/sports/horse-racing-general-challenge-circles-field-to-win-at-santa-anita.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=10 August 2017|date=5 March 2000}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=[[Claiming race]]}}
{{defn|defn= Race in which any competing horse is subject to be purchased for a preset price. A claim is made before the race and can only be acted upon by a licensed owner or their agent.<ref name="equibase defs"/> The price is set by the conditions of the race. If the horse wins prize money during the race, the money goes to the previous owner.<ref name=Lyons44>Price, et al. ''Lyons Press Horseman's Dictionary'' p. 44</ref>
}}

{{term|term=Closer}}
{{defn|defn= A horse that performs best during the final part of the race, usually coming from behind against most of its race competitors.<ref name="equibase defs"/>}}

{{term|term=Clubhouse turn}}
{{defn|defn=The turn to the right of the grandstand, so called because the clubhouse is usually to the right of the general stands<ref name="OaklawnTerms">{{cite web|title=Racing Terms|url=http://www.oaklawn.com/racing-101/racing-terms/|website=www.oaklawn.com|accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Conditions Book}}
{{defn|defn= Racetracks publish a Conditions Book listing the upcoming stakes that set the eligibility requirements and any restrictions for a horse running in a race, such as age, sex, state, province or country bred, number of wins, and amount of money won."<ref>[https://www.equibase.com/static/horsemen/horsemenareaCB.html?SAP=TN Equibase list of race track Conditions Books] Retrieved August 6, 2018</ref>}}

{{term|term=Connections}}
{{defn|defn= The owner and trainer of a horse. The term can also be extended to other members of a racing team or partnership.<ref name="equibase defs"/>}}

{{glossary end}}

==D==
{{glossary}}	
{{term|term=[[Dead heat (racing)|Dead heat]]}}
{{defn|defn= Term to denote a tie at the finish of the race between two or more horses.<ref name="equibase defs"/> A tie with three horses is very rare.<ref>{{cite web|title=Triple dead heat took place at Aqueduct Racetrack in 1944|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/more-sports/triple-dead-heat-place-aqueduct-racetrack-1944-article-1.2247161|website=NY Daily News|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Derby}}
{{defn|defn= A stakes race for three-year-olds.<ref name="equibase defs"/> As of 2016, there are over 20 derbies in the United States, often named for the racetrack or the state in which the race is run.<ref>{{cite web|title=Graded Stakes in the United States|url=https://www.toba.org/graded-stakes/races.aspx|website=www.toba.org|accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=[[Did not finish]] (DNF)}}
{{defn|defn= A horse that did not finish the race, for any of a number of reasons}}

{{glossary end}}

==E==
[[File:Eighth Pole DSC 0144 (4217599103).jpg|thumb|Horses going past the eighth pole at Santa Anita Park]]
{{glossary}}
{{term|term=Eased}}
{{defn|defn=When a jockey deliberately slows down a horse during a race, often to prevent injury or harm to the horse.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{term|term=Eighth pole}}
{{defn|defn=A pole to signal that the finish line is one-eighth of a mile away.<ref name="DRF terms" /> Eighth poles are green and white striped<ref name="WA Thoroughbred"/>}}

{{glossary end}}

==F==
{{glossary}}
{{term|term=Far turn}}
{{defn|defn=The turn off the backstretch into the homestretch.<ref name="OaklawnTerms" /> So called because it is farthest from the finish line.}}

{{term|term=Fast pace}}
{{defn|defn=When the leading horses in a race set fractional times that are substantially faster than normal for the distance.<ref name="equibase defs" />}}

{{term|term=Front-runner}}
{{defn|defn= A horse that has a preferred running style to run at or near the head of the field;<ref name="equibase defs"/> such horses generally lead or try to lead.<ref name="DRF terms" /> ''Compare:'' stalker, closer. ''See also'' Pacemaker, "rabbit"}}

{{term|term=[[Furlong]]}}
{{defn|defn= A distance equal to 220 yards ({{convert|1/8|mi|m|disp=x|&nbsp;or&nbsp;}})<ref name="Boardman 100">{{cite book|last=Boardman|first= Samuel Lane|title=Handbook of the turf|year=1910|publisher=Orange Judd Co|location=New York|page=100|url=http://hdl.handle.net/2027/pst.000000275439?urlappend=%3Bseq=104}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=[[Furosemide]]}}
{{defn|defn=Generic name of a medication used to treat bleeders, also commonly known by the trade name Lasix.<ref name="DRF terms" /> Indicated on past performance tables by the letter L.<ref name="DRF-PPs">{{cite web|title=Daily Racing Form: How To Use DRF - Past Performances|url=http://www1.drf.com/help/help_drf_pp.html|website=www1.drf.com|accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=[[Futurity (horse race)|Futurity]]}}
{{defn|defn= A race for two-year-old horses for which they have been nominated for entry while still a foal; the owners make payments over time to maintain the horse's eligibility.  Purses are usually large<ref name="equibase defs">{{cite web|last=Staff|title=Industry Glossary|url=http://www.equibase.com/newfan/glossary-full.cfm|publisher=Equibase company|accessdate=2013-08-27}}</ref>}}

{{glossary end}}

==G==
{{glossary}}
{{term|term=[[Graded stakes race]]}}
{{defn|defn= A classification system begun in 1973 to rank stakes races in North America, similar to the [[Group races]] of Europe. Roman numerals (I, II, or III) are used to designate the race classification.}}

{{glossary end}}

==H==
{{glossary}}

{{term|term=Half-brother, half-sister}}
{{defn|defn=Horses who are out of the same dam, but sired by different stallions.  Only horses with the same dam are considered half-siblings.<ref name="equibase defs" />}}

{{term|term=[[Handicap (horse racing)|Handicap]]}}
{{defn|defn= 1. A race designed to create equality by the horses being assigned different, specific weights determined by the track handicapper based on an assessment of each entrant's potential.<ref name="Equibase codes">{{cite web|title=Codes and Definitions|url=http://www.equibase.com/newfan/codes.cfm|website=Equibase.com|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref> 2. The process of selecting winners based on past performances.<ref name="equibase defs"/> 3.  The amount of weight, sometimes called an impost, carried by the horse.}}

{{term|term=Handily}}
{{defn|defn=Working or racing with moderate effort, more than a breeze.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{term|term=Hand ride}}
{{defn|defn= When the jockey urges a horse just with his/her hands and does not use the whip.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{term|term=Handle}}
{{defn|defn=The amount wagered in the various pari-mutuel pools for either a specified race, program (ie, all races at a given track on a given day), meeting or year.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{term|term=Head of the stretch, top of the stretch}}
{{defn|defn= The beginning of the homestretch.<ref name="equibase defs"/>}}

{{term|term=Hit the board}}
{{defn|defn=To finish in the top four placings, literally, to appear on the tote board.<ref name="Staff">{{cite web|last=Staff|title=Horse Racing glossary  G-P|url=http://www.ildado.com/horse_racing_glossary02.html|publisher=ildado.com|accessdate=20 December 2013}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Homestretch or stretch}}
{{defn|defn= The final straight section of the track leading to the finish.<ref name="equibase defs"/>}}

{{glossary end}}

==I==
{{glossary}}
{{term|term=In the money}}
{{defn|defn=1.  For a horse to finish in the top three placings, where bettors win money.  2. Less often, for the horse to finish in the top four, where the horses win prize money.<ref name="Staff"/>}}

{{term|term=Inquiry}}
{{defn|defn=1) When track stewards review the race to determine if there was an infraction of the rules. 2) When the "inquiry" sign is placed on the tote board. Inquiries lodged by a jockey are called objections.<ref name="equibase defs" />}}

{{glossary end}}

