{{glossary}}
{{term|term=Juvenile}}
{{defn|defn= Two-year-old horses.<ref name="equibase defs"/>}}

{{glossary end}}

==L==
{{glossary}}
{{term|term=Lasix}}
{{defn|defn= See Furosemide, above.}}

{{term|term=[[Horse length|Length]]}}
{{defn|defn= Used to describe the distance between horses during a race and at the finish line. One length is approximately {{convert|8|ft|m|disp=x|&nbsp;or&nbsp;}} and represents the length of one horse.<ref name="crickmore 26">{{cite book|last=Crickmore|first=H.G.|title=Dictionary or glossary of racing terms and slang.|year=1880|publisher=Rogers and Sherwood|location=New York|page=26|url=http://hdl.handle.net/2027/loc.ark:/13960/t8kd2qc6p?urlappend=%3Bseq=32}}</ref>}}

{{glossary end}}

==M==
{{glossary}}
{{term|term=Maiden race}}
{{defn|defn= Specific race for runners that have never won a race, usually by age, but not always.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{term|term=Margin}}
{{defn|defn=The distance between horses at a given point in the race, usually measured in lengths (see above). For the leader, it is the distance he/she was ahead of the second place horse. For other horses, it is the distance by which they trailed the leader. Shown in past performance charts as the small number after the horse's position at a given call.<ref name="DRF-PPs" />}}

{{term|term=Minus pool}}
{{defn|defn=When there is not enough money left in the parimutuel pool to pay the legally required minimum on each winning bet. This usually happens when one horse is very heavily bet upon. In these cases, the racing association usually is the entity that makes up the difference.<ref name="equibase defs" />}}

{{term|term=Morning line}}
{{defn|defn= The approximate odds before wagering begins and exact odds are established.<ref name="DRF terms">{{cite web|last=Staff|title=Help: Glossary of Horse Racing Terms|url=http://www1.drf.com/help/help_glossary.html|publisher=Daily Racing Form|accessdate=13 June 2013}}</ref>}}

{{glossary end}}

==N==
{{glossary}}
{{term|term=New shooter}}
{{defn|defn= A horse which skipped the [[Kentucky Derby]] to run in the [[Preakness Stakes]]<ref name="DRF shooter">{{cite web|url=http://www.drf.com/news/new-shooters-preakness-have-strength-numbers|title=New shooters in Preakness have strength in numbers|last=Hersh|first=Marcus|work=Daily Racing Form|date=May 12, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> or [[Belmont Stakes]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/sports/coburn-s-reaction-simply-sour-grapes|title=Coburn's reaction simply sour grapes|last=Carp|first=Steve|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|date=June 7, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Nom de course}}
{{defn|defn= A name, usually a pseudonym, used by a racehorse owner under which their horse is registered to compete.<ref name="DRF terms" /> }}

{{term|term=Nose}}
{{defn|defn= The shortest margin of victory in a race.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{glossary end}}

==O==
{{glossary}}
{{term|term=Oaks}}
{{defn|defn= Stakes race for three-year-old fillies.<ref name="equibase defs"/>}}

{{term|term=Odds-on}}
{{defn|defn=Odds of less than even money ($1 to $1). A winning bet returns the amount wagered plus the ratio specified by the odds. A winner at a payoff of under $4.00 for a $2 bet is "odds on."<ref name="OaklawnTerms" />}}

{{term|term=Optional claiming}}
{{defn|defn= A race where a horse can either meet the conditions of the race or be entered as a claimer.<ref name=BrisnetClassifications>{{cite web|title=Race Classifications|url=http://www.brisnet.com/cgi-bin/static.cgi?page=rclass|website=Brisnet.com|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Out of the money}}
{{defn|For a horse to finish worse than third, meaning that bettors do not win money.<ref name="Staff"/> Opposite of "in the money".}}
{{glossary end}}

==P==
[[File:Finish post.jpg|thumb|The finish post at [[Belmont Park]]]]
{{glossary}}
{{term|term=Pace}}
{{defn|defn= The speed of a race. To run a horse "off the pace" means that the horse will not be in the lead for the early part of the race but will advance to the front shortly before the finish of the race.<ref name=stevens>{{cite book|last=Stevens|first=Gary|title=The Perfect Ride|year=2002|publisher=Citadel Press Books|location=New York|isbn=0806523611|page=219|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SYcw6P6o39YC&lpg=PA219&dq=%22rate%22%20off%20pace%20glossary&pg=PA219#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Pacemaker}}
{{defn|defn= A horse who goes to the front of the field to ensure a suitable pace, usually to set up the race for a stablemate who runs off the pace. Also called a Rabbit. In contrast, a Frontrunner is trying to win the race.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McGrath|first1=J A|title=Pacemakers under scrutiny|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/horseracing/3013846/Pacemakers-under-scrutiny.html|website=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Pacesetter}}
{{defn|defn= A frontrunner. ''Compare'': closer, stalker}}

{{term|term=Paddock}}
{{defn|defn= Saddling and parading area where horses can be seen prior to the race.<ref name="equibase defs"/> ''See also [[paddock]] for agricultural uses.''}}

{{term|term=Past performances}}
{{defn|defn= A list of the horses in a race showing each horse's previous racing record, earnings, pedigree and so on.<ref name="equibase defs" />}}

{{term|term=[[Phenylbutazone]]}}
{{defn|defn=Generic term for a widely used analgesic medication in horses. Most common trade name is Butazolidin; often called "bute".<ref name="DRF terms" /> Shown on past performance tables as a B.<ref name="DRF-PPs"/>}}

{{term|term=Photo finish}}
{{defn|defn= A race result so close that the judges cannot decide the order of finish until they consult photographs taken of the race finish.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{term|term=Pinhook, pinhooking}}
{{defn|defn= Buying young race horses, usually yearlings, with an intent to resell later at a profit.<ref name="OxfordPinhook">{{cite web|title=pinhooking - definition of pinhooking in English {{!}} Oxford Dictionaries|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/pinhooking|website=Oxford Dictionaries|accessdate=9 April 2017}}</ref>''See also: Bloodstock agent''}} 

{{term|term=Place}}
{{defn|defn=Second position at finish. A place bet is a wager on a horse to finish first or second.<ref name="equibase defs" />}}

{{term|term=Pole}}
{{defn|defn=Markers placed at specific locations around the track marking the distance from the finish line, named after the distance remaining, not the distance run, i.e. the quarter pole, eighth pole, sixteenth pole each measure the distance left in the race.<ref name="DRF terms" /> One-sixteenth poles are black and white striped. Eighth poles are green and white. Quarter poles are red and white.<ref name="WA Thoroughbred"/>}}

{{term|term=Post}}
{{defn|defn= 1. The starting point of a race  2.  Post position (see below)  3. (verb) To reference or record a win.<ref name="equibase defs"/>}}

{{term|term=Post parade}}
{{defn|defn=When the horses in a race travel from the paddock to the starting gate ("post"), past the grandstands.<ref name="WA Thoroughbred"/>}}

{{term|term=Post position}}
{{defn|defn= The number of the individual stalls in the [[starting gate]] where horses will begin a race.<ref name="DRF terms" /> The first stall (#1 or inside position) is next to the [[Glossary of North American horse racing#R|rail]] at most racetracks with higher numbers on the outside of the track. Post position can be a hindrance or tactical advantage for horses depending on their racing style.<ref name=Durso>{{cite news|last=Durso|first=Joseph|title=Horse racing: Fly So Free Gets Post 1; It's Not the Favorite Spot|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/05/03/sports/horse-racing-fly-so-free-gets-post-1-it-s-not-the-favorite-spot.html|accessdate=July 4, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 3, 1991}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Pull up}}
{{defn|defn= To pull back on the reins to slowly stop a horse. Jockeys will typically ease a horse to a stop after passing the finish line or if there is a problem with the horse, such as injury, that necessitates a withdrawal from a race.<ref name="hammond 166">{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Gerald|title=The Language of Horse Racing|year=2000|publisher=Fitzroy Dearborn|location=Chicago|isbn=1579582761|page=166|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CJ4zH2P_6mMC&lpg=PA166&dq=%22pull%20up%22%20horseracing&pg=PA166#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>}}

{{glossary end}}

