{{defn|defn= A pole to signal that the finish line is one-quarter of a mile away.<ref name="DRF terms" /> Quarter poles are red and white striped.<ref name="WA Thoroughbred"/>}}

{{glossary end}}

==R==
[[File:Generic racetrack diagram.png|thumb|upright=1.2|Generic left-handed racetrack diagram: A = finish line, B = grandstand, C/black = [[Glossary of North American horse racing#C|chute]], Yellow = [[Glossary of North American horse racing#H|homestretch]], Red = [[Glossary of North American horse racing#C|Clubhouse turn]], Blue = [[Glossary of North American horse racing#B|backstretch]], Green = [[Glossary of North American horse racing#F|Far turn]], gray inside line = rail and the white center is the infield. Black dots note standard locations of the  [[Glossary of North American horse racing#P|poles]] that measure distance to the finish.]]
{{glossary}}

{{term|term=Rabbit}}
{{defn|defn=A horse with speed entered to set a fast early pace to help the chances of a stablemate.<ref name="equibase defs"/> Also known as a Pacemaker}}

{{term|term=Racecard}}
{{defn|defn=A program for a race day that lists the individual races and the name, age, and sex of each horse scheduled to compete along with their recent performances plus the name of their jockey, trainer and owner.<ref name="DRF terms"/>}}

{{term|term=Racemare}}
{{defn|defn= Female horse ([[mare]]) who has competed in sanctioned Thoroughbred races.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{term|term=Race meet}} 
{{defn|defn= A racetrack meeting over a designated number of specific days to run Thoroughbred races.<ref name="Cambridge Dictionary" />}}

{{term|term=Racetrack or racecourse}}
{{defn|defn= A flat surface made of dirt, grass (turf) or synthetic material, usually arranged in an oval, where races are conducted. Races can either be run in a counterclockwise (left-handed) or clockwise (right-handed) direction around the track. Left-handed, dirt tracks are the predominant form in the United States, mostly due to tradition.<ref name="ashforth">{{cite web|last=Ashforth|first=David|title=Why are all American racetracks left-handed? David Ashforth reveals how a long forgotten racetrack set the tone for racing in the US. (25 April 2010)|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Why+are+all+American+racetracks+left-handed%3F+David+Ashforth+reveals...-a0224796876|publisher=The Racing Post|accessdate=13 June 2013}}</ref> Tracks typically consist of two turns, a backstretch, a straight (or homestretch) arranged around a central infield and various surrounding structures such as the finish line and stands for spectators.<ref name="ashforth" />}}

{{term|term=Rail}}
{{defn|defn= Inside fence on a racetrack.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{term|term=Rank }}
{{defn|defn= A horse that is fractious and hard for the jockey to handle.<ref>{{cite web|last=Staff|title=Horse Racing glossary  Q-Z|url=http://www.ildado.com/horse_racing_glossary03.html|publisher=ildado.com|accessdate=15 September 2013}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Rank outsider}}
{{defn|defn= A horse that is not expected to win a race.<ref>{{cite web|last=Staff|title=RanK Outsider|url=http://dictionary.cambridge.org/us/dictionary/british/rank-outsider|publisher=Cambridge Dictionaries Online|accessdate=15 September 2013}}</ref>}}

{{term|term=Rate}}
{{defn|defn= A deliberate action by the jockey to keep a horse "[[Glossary of North American horse racing#P|off the pace]]".<ref name=stevens />}}

{{term|term=Ridden out}}
{{defn|defn= When a horse is not whipped but rather works out or wins with a strong hand ride.<ref name="DRF terms" />}}

{{glossary end}}

