[[File:Mangaphas Aspron Trachy.jpg|thumb|right|250px|''[[Aspron]]'' ''trachy'' minted by the usurper [[Theodore Mankaphas]]]]
The term '''''trachy''''' ({{lang-el|τραχύ}}), plural '''''trachea''''' (τραχέα), meaning "rough" or "uneven", was used to describe the cup-shaped (incorrectly often called "[[scyphate]]") [[Byzantine coins]] struck in the 11th–14th centuries.{{sfn|ODB|loc="Trachy" (Ph. Grierson), p. 2101}} The term was properly applied to coins of [[electrum]], [[billon (alloy)|billon]], or [[copper]], and not to the gold ''[[hyperpyra]]''.{{sfn|ODB|loc="Trachy" (Ph. Grierson), p. 2101}}

